  "prompt": "Who are IAS Aspirants?",
  "response": "IAS aspirants are individuals who aspire to become officers in the Indian Administrative Service (IAS), which is one of the premier civil services in India. The IAS is responsible for implementing government policies and administering public services at various levels, including state and central government. \n\nTo become an IAS officer, aspirants must clear the Civil Services Examination (CSE), which is conducted by the Union Public Service Commission (UPSC). The examination consists of three stages: \n\n1. **Preliminary Examination**: This is a screening test that comprises objective-type questions. It serves to shortlist candidates for the next stage.\n\n2. **Main Examination**: This part includes subjective-type questions and is more comprehensive, testing candidates' depth of knowledge across various subjects, as well as essay writing and general studies.\n\n3. **Interview (Personality Test)**: Successful candidates from the Main Examination are called for a personal interview, which assesses their personality, communication skills, and suitability for a career in civil services.\n\nIAS aspirants often undergo extensive preparation, which may include studying a wide range of subjects such as history, geography, polity, economics, current affairs, and general knowledge. Many also attend coaching classes, participate in study groups, or utilize online resources to enhance their chances of success in this competitive examination.",
